The coronavirus aid bill provides $25 billion in grants to U.S. passenger airlines, granted they do not furlough or cut the pay of their workers through Sept. 30.
United is seeking to cut its costs by asking employees to take unpaid leave, while some staff is working a reduced schedule.
Airlines including United, are seeking to exhaust voluntary leaves, including early retirement plans, before turning to furloughs or layoffs.
U.S. airlines, which employ some 750,000 people, have been among the businesses hardest hit by the coronavirus.
Airlines have slashed flights, parked hundreds of jets and asked thousands of employees to take unpaid leave, while they tap credit lines to shore up cash.